In mathematics, the '''bondage number''' of a nonempty [[Graph (discrete mathematics)|graph]] is the [[cardinality]] of the smallest set ''E'' of edges such that the [[domination number]] of the graph with the edges ''E'' removed is strictly greater than the domination number of the original graph.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0012-365X(90)90348-L | title=The bondage number of a graph | journal=Discrete Mathematics | date=1990 | volume=86 | issue=1-3 | pages=47‚Äì57 | first=John Frederick | last=Fink}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0012-365X(94)90111-2 | title=Bounds on the bondage number of a graph | journal=Discrete Mathematics | date=1994 | volume=128 | issue=1-3 | pages=173‚Äì177 | first=Bert L. | last=Hartnell}}</ref> The concept was introduced by Fink et. al.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1155/2013/595210| title = On Bondage Numbers of Graphs: A Survey with Some Comments| journal = International Journal of Combinatorics| volume = 2013| issue = 1 | pages = 1| year = 2013| last1 = Xu | first1 = J. M. }}</ref> == References == {{reflist}}
